LEAKING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PACKAGE CALLED IN. PICKED UP BY RESPONDER, TRANSPORTED TO HAZMAT AREA AND PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP. ONE CAP WAS LOOSE AND CAME OFF THE BOTTLE.

FULLY LABELED HAZ-MAT SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED WET IN APPEARANCE ON BOTTOM OF BOX AND EMITTING A SOUR ODOR BY THE SORTER ON BOXLINE-4. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PKG HE EVACUATED THE AREA AND NOTIFIED THE IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR. DMP WAS CONTACTED AND WITHIN 2 MIN. A RESPONDER ARRIVED, DONNING THE PROPER PPE. AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE   APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET, THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED (NO SPILLAGE OUTSIDE OF CARTON) AND THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT ON 1 OF 4 (1 GAL) PLASTIC JUGS THE CAP COMPLETELY POPPED OFF, CAUSING APPROX. 12 OZ OF THE PRODUCT TO LEAK THROUGH THE BREACH. FORTUNATELY THE JUG WAS IN A PLASTIC BAG, WHICH MINIMIZED THE AMOUNT OF LIQUID THAT REACHED THE OUTER CARTON. THE INNER PACKING MATERIAL CONSISTED OF A SINGLEWALL CORRUGATED DIVIDER AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A SINGLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 44 LBS/IN EDGE CRUSH TEST (ECT).

column168: At 0445 hrs. while the WLE Brewster Yard Car Inspector was inspecting and Inbound train, he noticed car ULTX 956246 Hissing from on top the car.  He also notice and odor coming from the car.  He called the Brewster Yardmaster who then called myself, john Vergis Environmental Officer for WLE.  When i came out to look at the car I noticed there was not seal on the protective housing lid.  I opened the lid and found that the vapor valve was leaking through the valve plug.  I tried to tighten the valve handle and the leak stopped.  I then tightened the valve plug.  I also noticed that the liquid valve on the A end of the car had its plug missing and was laying off to the side.  i reinstalled the valve and tightened appropriately.  I then check the plug on the B end liquid valve and it was loose so I tightened it also.  I then released the car for service.   NARRI:  5(4+5)X2=47                                        Cause Code:  110,390
column169: Better Car securement procedures need followed.

column168: At 0445 hrs. on 4/20/2018, the WLE Brewster Yard Car Inspector while inspecting an inbound train, notice car UTLX 956246 hissing from on top the car and an odor was noticed.  He called the Brewster Yard Master who then called myself, John Vergis Environmental Officer for WLE.  I came out to look at the car and I saw that there was no seal on the protective housing lid of the car.  I opened the lid and found that the vapor valve was leaking through the valve plug.  I tried tightening the valve handle and the leak stopped.  I then tightened the valve plug.  I also noticed that the liquid valve on the A end had the plug missing and was laying off to the side.  I reinstalled the plug  in the valve and tightened appropriately.  I checked the plug in the B end liquid valve and it was loose also.  I tightened it.  I then released the car for service.   NARRI: 5(4+5)X2=47                                                     Cause Code: 110,118,390

column168: The spec 57 tanks containing DOT paint were on a north bound train, it met a southbound train that was holed up in Clear Siding, the leak was discovered during the roll by.  The trailer and flatcar that contained the paint, was set out in the siding.  ARRC environmental folks were called out and mobilized to the site.  Notifications were made, and a response contractor was called to help with the cleanup.  The leak was stabilized and the cleanup was completed the next day.  The tank was emptied, the paint was placed into drums and will be disposed of.  The spilled paint was scraped up and put into drums.  Most of the paint that leaked out the rear door of the container spilled onto the flat car, approximately one gallon of paint hit the ground, it was drops of paint over a couple of miles, the drops of paint were confined to the ballast area between the rails.  It appears that the tank failed on the bottom side of the tank.  It looked like the failure was on a seam of the tank.
column169: An inspection of the tank before loading may have revealed something, although the failure was in a place that it would have been tough to detect. The roll by inspection of the train by the other train crew worked.  It detected the leaky tank/car.

column43: KIDDE MULTIPURPOSE DRY CHEMICAL FIRE EXTINGUISHER
column168: DURING THE PRELOAD, THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER WAS CALLED TO THE ORANGE BELT TO RESPOND TO A PACKAGE LEAKING YELLOW POWDER FROM IT'S CLOSURES. THE PACKAGE WAS ALREADY ON THE FLOOR WHERE THE LOADER HAD PLACED IT WHEN HE NOTICED IT WAS LEAKING. THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER ACTED IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE LEAKING PACKAGE DECISION TREE   APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL. OUTER PACKAGING HAD NO MARKINGS/LABELS INDICATING THAT CONTENTS WERE HAZARDOUS. HOWEVER, THE INNER PACKAGING, 2 FIBERBOARD BOXES CONTAINING 1 FIRE EXTINGUISHER EACH, WERE MARKED WITH LIMITED QUANTITY DIAMOND LABELS. ONCE PACKAGE WAS BROUGHT TO THE DAMAGE PROCESSING AREA, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE SAFETY PIN ON ONE OF THE FIRE EXTINGUISHER LEVERS HAD COME LOOSE, ALLOWING THE LEVER TO BECOME COMPRESSED, RELEASING THE CONTENTS OF THE EXTINGUISHER. THE RESPONDER CALLED THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SUPPORT CENTER PRIOR TO INPUTTING THIS REPORT   SPOKE WITH HMSC REPRESENTATIVE DARIAN, REFERENCE # 071738.
column169: THE EXTERNAL PACKAGING SHOULD HAVE BEEN LABELED WITH A LIMITED QUANTITY DIAMOND LABEL. IN MY OPINION THIS WOULD HOPEFULLY HAVE LED TO OVERALL MORE CAREFUL PACKAGE HANDLING(THOUGH THERE'S NO INDICATION THAT IMPROPER PACKAGE HANDLING ACTUALLY TOOK PLACE LEADING UP TO THIS INCIDENT). ADDITIONALLY AND OF POTENTIAL SIGNIFICANCE, THE ORIENTATION ARROWS PRESET ON THE EXTERNAL PACKAGING WERE ESSENTIALLY MEANINGLESS AS THE ITEMS WITHIN WERE NOT PACKED UPRIGHT.

column168: The driver was exiting off interstate I-55 onto Goodman Rd. and was traveling too fast to make the left  turn onto Goodman Rd. The truck and trailer overturned onto the left side. Sand was available to cover the release and spill booms were in place.

column25: World Fuel Services Inc dba CarterEnergy
column168: JUAN JASSO (CARTERENERGY FUEL TRANSPORT DRIVER) WAS TRAVELING NB ON HWY 281 N OR RHOME TX LOADED WITH 7500 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL. AN SUV DRIVEN BY JOE FRERICH WAS ALSO TRAVELING NB ON HWY 287 AND DRIVING AT A SLOW RATE OF SPEED DUE TO HAVING A SPARE TIRE ON HIS VEHICLE. TEXAS DEPT OF TRANSPORTATION ACC REPORT SUGGEST DID NOT SEE THE SLOWER VEHICLE AS HE APPROACHED FROM BEHIND. AT SOME POINT JUAN JASSO STEERED HARD TO THE LEFT CAUSING THE TANKER TO COMPLETE A 360 DEGREE ROLL OVER THE SUV ON THE ROADWAY. AFTER ROLLING THE TRANSPORT ENDED UP ON ITS WHEELS FACING SB IN THE MEDIAN BETWEEN THE SB AND NB LANES. THE TRAILERS FRONT COMPARTMENT WAS RUPTURED AND SPILLED 2632 GALLONS OF FUEL ONTO THE GROUND. EMT’S AIRLIFTED JUAN JASSO TO JOHN PETERSON MEDICAL CENTER IN FT WORTH WHERE HE WAS LATER PRONOUNCED DEAD. JOE FRENCH WAS ALSO TRANSPORTED TO JOHN PETERSON HOSPITAL AND TREATED FOR NON-LIFE THREATENING INJURIES. TAS ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTRACTED TO BEGIN HAZMAT CLEAN-UP OPERATIONS AND REMOVE LIQUID PRODUCT FROM THE DITCH AND THEN BEGAN TO REMOVE THE CONTAINMENT SOIL IN AN AREA APPX 6FT WIDE 1-3FT DEEP AND 200FT LONG. CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS PLACED ON PLASTIC SHEETING IN THE MEDIAN TEMPORARILY UNTIL OFF SITE TRANSPORTATION COULD BE SCHEDULED. CLEAN-UP OPERATIONS INCLUDING TRANSFERRING ALL CONTAMINATED SOIL/BACK FILLING WITH CLEAN SOIL/RESEEDING WAS COMPLETED ON APRIL 10TH.
column169: DRIVERS WERE BROUGHT IN AND BRIEFED ON ACC DETAILS THAT WERE MADE AVAILABLE AT THE TIME ON APRIL 5 AND 6TH BY CARTERENERGY VP OF TRANSPORTATION SHANNON STRINGER.  ADDITIONAL IN-HOUSE SAFETY TRAINING WAS COMPLETED REGARDING DISTRACTED DRIVING/DEFENSIVE DRIVING/CELL PHONE POLICY ON APRIL 24 AND 26 BY CARTERENERGY VP OF TRANSPORTATION/CARTERENERGY LOGISTICS DIRECTOR ANNETTE HURLEY AND CARTERENERGY SAFETY MANAGER.

column168: During the week of 4/16/18, Murphy contacted Eco-Energy’s transportation management team to find out if anything was known about red dyed diesel spilled at their location in Thomasville, Georgia. The spill reached a nearby creek and also caused the evacuation of a nearby school due to the fumes. Because Eco does not transport red dyed diesel, the team did not believe Eco was involved. Still, the Eco Energy transportation management team reach out to drivers in the area to see if they knew anything about the spill. All drivers denied knowledge of the diesel spill. The Murphy team later contacted Eco-Energy’s transportation management team to inform them of video footage in which a driver in what looks like an Eco truck pulls a hose to the other side of his truck right where the spill was located. Using our Peoplenet system, which shows which drivers are logged into which truck and where they are located at a given time, it was determined the driver was Jaron Coleman who was not scheduled to be at that location at that time.  The Director of Transportation called Mr. Coleman to ask about the incident. Mr. Coleman told the Transportation Director he needed to ‘check his notes’ and hung up. Within the hour, Mr. Coleman called back and told him he had accidentally loaded a full compartment of red dyed diesel. When he realized his mistake, he panicked and decided to get rid of the product. He drove to Thomasville and dumped approximately 3000 gallons in the grass. Eco’s transportation management team informed Murphy of what they learned and began to collect all the necessary contacts from Murphy to include the local authorities, federal and state EPA, and the remediation consultant. Mr. Coleman was arrested by the Thomasville Sheriff Department on April 27, 2018. The duration of the release was therefore from 4/16/18 through 4/19/18 when it was discovered and response measures ensued. For a detailed description of mitigation efforts, please see the attachments.
column169: This release was not due to equipment malfunction or insufficient operating procedures. This was a criminal offense conducted by an employee who loaded an unauthorized product and did not follow protocol for correcting a load and instead made an unlawful release of hazardous materials.

column168: AFTER PASSING THROUGH SHATTUCK, OKLAHOMA, ON US 283 SOUTH, A TOTE BECAME RUPTURED DURING TRANSPORTATION, WHILE SECURED ON THE BACK OF A FLATBED TRUCK. THE RUPTURE OCCURRED AS A RESULT OF A SECURMENT DEVICE UNEXPECTEDLY BEING JERKED LOOSE FROM ITS ANCHOR POINTS. ONE END OF THE DETACHED SECUREMENT DEVICE WAS PULLED BETWEEN TWO ADJACENT TOTES AND THE METAL ANCHOR ON THE DEVICE RUPTURED A PLASTIC TOTE, CAUSING IT TO LEAK A PORTION OF THE LIQUID MATERIAL. THE SECUREMENT DEVICE CAME LOSE, WHEN THE EXCESS STRAP MATERIAL, BECAME UN-TUCKED AND FELL UNDER THE TIRES ON THE DRIVE AXLE OF THE TRUCK. THIS CAUSED THE STRAP TO BE SUDDENLY JERKED LOOSE, WHICH BECOME UNATTACHED FROM ITS ANCHOR POINTS. ONCE LOOSE, THE STRAP WA PULLED BETWEEN TWO ADJACENT TOTES AND THE LOOSE ANCHOR ON THE STRAP DAMAGED ONE OF THE TOTES ON THE SIDE, WITH AN APPROXIMATE 12 INCH CUT NEAR IN THE MIDDLE OF THE TOTE. EACH TOTE WAS SECURED OVER THE TOP WITH TWO 2 INCH SYNTHETIC STRAPS, WHICH MADE SURE THE DAMAGED TOTE REMAINED SECURED TO THE TRUCK DURING THE ENTIRE EVENT.   THE DRIVER BECAME IMMEDIATELY AWARE OF THE LOOSE STRAP WHEN IT WAS JERKED LOOSE BY THE TIRES AND SAFELY BROUGHT THE TRUCK TO A STOP. HE QUICKLY NOTICED THE LEAKING TOTE, AND WITH ASSISTANCE FROM A CO-DRIVER, THEY QUICKLY MITIGATED THE SPILLING LIQUID FROM THE DAMAGED TOTE AND CAPTURED AS MUCH OF THE MATERIAL AS POSSIBLE. MOST OF THE MATERIAL WAS CAUGHT IN OTHER CONTAINERS AND THE REMAINING MATERIAL WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER EMPTY TOTE ON THE TRUCK.
column169: UPON SECURING CARGO WITH SYNTHETIC STRAPS, IT IS SUGGESTED THE REMAINING LOOSE EXCESS STRAP MATERIAL BE ROLLED UP AND TUCKED TIGHTLY BETWEEN EACH STRAP AND THE CARGO WHEN POSSIBLE, AND/OR ADDITIONALLY SECURE THE EXCESS STRAP TO THE RATCHETING DEVICE WITH AS MANY PLASTIC TIES AS NECESSARY.

column168: On April 8, 2018, Dupre Logistics (Ref#04082018THOMW) notified ERTS in regards to a diesel fuel release. According to the caller, the driver of tractor (500102) 306/406 tanker (22102) was offloading product into a underground storage tank, when it over-filled. Approximately 50-gallons of diesel fuel has been released to the concrete and possibly a drain. Contractor indicated that the area impacted is 100' x 5' of concrete. Contractor estimates approximately 20-gallons of diesel released. Contractor completed work and departed site. A total estimated amount released was approximately 20-25 Gallons of diesel fuel that impacted the concrete / asphalt, storm drain, and a small area of soil. The asphalt / concrete was impacted by a 60'x3' area of diesel fuel. Diesel impacted the soil in a 5'x5'. The drain had been minimally impacted (estimated less than 1/2 of a gallon released). This spill apparently happened earlier in the day and by the time the contractor arrived and inspected the drain there was a small amount of granular absorbents laying in the drain but no sheen on the free standing water. The outflow area was inspected and it led to an outflow pipe approximately 30' away that flowed to a ditch. The ditch was inspected and no impact was discovered. HEPACO flushed the drain and placed a drum at the end to capture the impacted water (Please see in the photos). The NRC had already been contacted by Dodges Gas Station Earlier and report #1208827 had been generated (ERTS was instructed to contact EPA Region 4 800-241-1754 during daytime hours to obtain a copy of the report).   The soil was hand remediated and the asphalt was impacted with granular absorbents. One - 55 Gallon Steel Drum of impacted waste water was generated and two - 55 Gallon Drums of Diesel impacted soil and absorbents were generated

column168: Original comments:  Damage to the package was discovered by a loader on the van lines. Local security footage was reviewed to try and determine if the package was damaged before arrival to the station, on its way to the van line or, in the process of being loaded. However, nothing conclusive could be determined.   Damage appears to have been caused when the package suffered an impact to its side. The box and the leaking bottle both had been dented inward. The impact caused the seal to be broken. The cap was still on the bottle, slowing the loss of the liquid. Given the relatively large amount spilled in comparison to the size in the gap of the seal,it is my belief that the damage was cause before the package arrived to this station. It appears to have been a slow, sustained leak.  New Comments:

column168: THE DRIVER WAS DISTRACTED WHILE LOOKING AT HIS PHONE TO REVIEW GOOGLE MAPS, INSTEAD OF HAVING THIS GOING THROUGH HIS BLUETOOTH DEVICE. HE STRUCK A BRIDGE WHICH BROKE THE SUSPENSION ON THE RIGHT FRONT STEER AXLE. WHEN HE EXITED THE BRIDGE IT FORCED HIM SUDDENLY TO THE RIGHT CAUSING HIM TO GO OFF INTO AN EMBANKMENT. HE STRUCK A TREE WITH THE PASSENGER SIDE OF THE CAB AND IT PUSH THE RIGHT FRONT CORNER OF THE TRACTOR INTO THE TANKER CAUSING IT TO BEND A FEW INCHES. THIS CREATED A CRACK IN THE UPPER PORTION OF THE SEAM THAT WAS ABOUT 4 INCHES LONG CAUSING PRODUCT TO LEAK. THERE WAS NO FLOW OF PRODUCT TOWARD THE NEARBY CREEK.  USES, UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, WAS CALLED IMMEDIATELY AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE FOR CLEAN-UP. THEY SECURED THE SCENE AND BEGAN THE PROCESS OF CLEAN UP WITH VARIOUS METHODS SUCH AS FOAM, SPILL CONTAINMENT, VACUUMS AND GROUND WORK.  THE CLEAN-UP TOOK ABOUT 5-6 HOURS THEN THE TOW COMPANY WAS ABLE TO REMOVE THE TRUCK AND TRAILER. USES CONTINUED WITH CLEAN-UP EFFORTS FOR A FEW MORE HOURS AFTER THE TANKER WAS REMOVED FROM THE SCENE.

column168: Original comments:  Driver took package out for delivery today. He returned the package to station at end of day requesting inspection because he could smell strong fumes coming from package. There were no visible signs of leaking from the package. Package was clearly marked as a hazardous material package. QA inspected the package and confirmed one of the cans of paint within package was leaking. Package contains 2-1 gallon metal cans of Wasser MC-MIOZINC 100 Standard Green paint. Outer boxing had the capacity of holding 4 - 1 gallon cans but only 2 cans were packed within this box. Each can of paint was enclosed within an individual plastic bag and zip-tied closed. This bagging contained the leakage almost completely. A very small amount of the leakage came through the bag got on the inner boxing, however, there was no leakage contaminant on the other bagged gallon of paint within the box. There was paper packing within the boxing to protect & stabilize items throughout the shipping process. Estimated leakage amount within package and cause of failure because can of paint within bagging is completely covered in product and it cannot be clearly determined  what caused this item to leak. column168: the subject tank car was found to be leaking in Minot, ND from the base of the "A end" liquid valve, the base of the vapor valve and a very small leak emitting from the base of the SRV. initial attempts from the local BNSF Responder to tighten the nuts securing the valves was unsuccessful. Once the responding contractor arrived they successfully tightened the nuts securing these appurtenances to the pressure plate and stopped the leaks. Each nut on the vapor and liquid valve was turned approximately a quarter to an eighth of a turn. The SRV nuts only required slight adjustment to stop the leak.
column169: additional preventative maintenance and/or periodic re-torqueing of the nuts on all fittings may be in order in the future

column168: Carrier driver noticed hazmat splashing from the CTMV and pulled over to stop.  After about 10 seconds, liquid product stopped sloshing out.  He saw that a 3" fusible vent cap was installed on the rear washout nipple, and the center disc was missing, leaving a 2" opening.  He called for assistance, and after about 4 hours, a Hazmat responder installed a cleanout cover, stopping the vapor release.  Quality Event #68828
column169: There was no evidence of a thermal or pressure incident that would cause a fusible vent cap to vent, and Carrier's investigation found impact marks on the fusible vent cap.  Therefore, we suggest that DOT consider outreach or broad training to carriers, shippers and consignees on following manufacturer's closure instructions.

column168: Carrier was taking the portable tank to the next carrier at the port  The port's entry guard told our driver s/he smelled product, and would not allow our vehicle to enter.  Our driver parked in a safe area, and walked around the vehicle.  He saw product at the top rear of the portable tank, and called for assistance.  The responding HazMat crew inspected the tank and closed an open inlet valve.  We estimate that it was about 75 minutes from when the guard noticed the release to when the HazMat crew closed the inlet valve and stopped the vapor release.  Event #68835.
column169: Recommended DOT consider an outreach program to shippers about checking that openings and valves at the top of CTMV's and portable tanks are secure.

column168: An odor was detected around UTLX 950184.  Upon inspection of the car, the liquid line valve was open on the A End, the plug was tool tight, however the vapor was escaping past the plug.  The valve was closed, Teflon tape was applied to the plug which was re-secured to tool tight and the release was stopped.  Upon further inspection, the valve was determined to be defective and the release was secured with secondary containment.

To be clear, there was no issues with the unloading valves as I had flagged in the report.  I wasn't sure what to select as this was completely human error.  The drivers are trained to use 5-10 psi air pressure to unload on this account as many of their products foam.  She admitted that she was using 15psi and was thinking about a different training.  She said if she is aware that a product foams she does only use 5-10psi.  We did not have it flagged as a foaming product in our system.  As a result at the end of the offload 5 gallons spilled out, some went in a containment area and some overshot the containment berm.
column169: The driver has had a few spills on this account so the decision was made to pull her from the account.  She decided to resign and move on to another career choice.  We have since updated the commodity to reflect that it foams so future drivers will have that awareness.

column168: Initially the customer didn't have enough room for the product.  She is not allowed to be by the tank but the facility provided her with the capacity and how much was in it.  After running some numbers we were going to be 168 gallons over the 90% safety cut off.  They said they would make room.  A bit later they came out and said they moved 200 gallons out.  When she felt her hoses go light she shut down right at the same time the plant was radioing over the 2 way radios to shut down that it was shooting out of the tank.  One person told her it was approximately 60 gallons of foam.  We don't know if it went into a containment area or how they specifically cleaned it up, just that they did clean it up.
column169: On this account we train the drivers not to exceed 5-10psi as alot of the customer products foam.  That said we missed training her on this account and she followed her training from another account that says not to go over 15psi.  I believe the mix of a little higher air pressure (causing some foam) with not a lot of headspace in the customer tank ultimately caused this to happen.  We have brought her in and had her go through the right training.

column168: While the hazmat was being loaded by the shipper, shipper personnel noticed that the product was leaking on the belly of the tanker near the internal valve. The trailer lining Durakane 441 failed which caused a leak in the sump; a pin hole was observed in the side of of the sump nozzle area.  We believe normal pressure differential created by product flow through this neck degraded the lining.  The duration of the release is estimated at 15 minutes. The CTMV was located in the shipper's containment bay and the release was contained.   Our Reference No. 68979

column168: ON 4/19/2018 AT 10:31. KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY'S (KCS) ENVIRONMENTAL AND HAZMAT DEPARTMENT RECEIVED NOTICE THAT FRA INSPECTOR RAYMOND DIEHL, WHILE CONDUCTING AN INSPECTION IN THE KCS ALEXANDRIA, LA YARD, CITED NATX 160221, A TANK CAR CONTAINING UN1824, CLASS 8, FOR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ADHERING TO THE LEFT AND RIGHT SIDE OF THE TANK CAR AND FOR ONE OF SIX MANWAY SECUREMENT BOLTS, LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT. A RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS DEPLOYED TO INVESTIGATE AND SECURE THE PACKAGE.  UPON ARRIVAL, THE RESPONDER FOUND ONE OF SIX MANWAY SECUREMENT BOLTS LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT. THE MANWAY WAS OPENED AND IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT NO MANWAY GASKET HAD BEEN APPLIED. A NEW RIM NOZZLE GASKET WAS INSTALLED, THE MANWAY BOLTS TIGHTENED TOOL TIGHT. ONCE THE MANWAY COVER WAS SECURE, THE CAR WAS RELEASED BACK INTO TRANSPORTATION.  FILE NOTE: ITEM 19-THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED BASED ON THE BEST INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF FILING. THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS A 'BULK' SHIPMENT, AKA ONE CAR LOAD, THEREFORE THE EXACT AMOUNT OFFERED IN THIS PACKAGE IS NOT KNOWN TO THE CARRIER. THIS CARRIER DOES NOT HAVE ACCESS TO MASS BALANCE DATA WHICH CAN EXACTLY QUANTIFY THIS VALUE.
column169: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) NOTIFIED SHIPPER OF THIS RELEASE. NON-ACCIDENTAL RELEASE (NAR) CAN BE DEVASTATING ON SEVERAL DIFFERENT LEVELS. THEY CAN CAUSE PERSONAL INJURY, ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE, DISRUPT RAIL YARDS, ADJACENT FACILITIES AND COMMUNITIES, AND SNARL TRAIN OPERATIONS FOR HUNDREDS OF MILES AND BOTH DIRECTIONS. NARS ARE TROUBLESOME TO ALL BECAUSE THEY ARE, BY AND LARGE, PREVENTABLE. FOR NON ACCIDENT RELEASES (A.K.A. PACKAGE CLOSURE ISSUES SUCH AS THIS), THE SHIPPER IS REQUESTED TO CONDUCT A ROOT-CAUSE INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE(S) OF RELEASE AND TO THEN FACILITATE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. IT IS REQUESTED THAT THE SHIPPER SHARE THEIR FINDINGS WITH KCS. (PLEASE DIRECT YOUR ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION RESULTS CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO STEVE MCNEALY, KCS RAILWAY, P.O. column168: On April 8, 2018, John N John Truck Line Inc. notified ERTS in regards to a tractor 307/407 tanker roll-over accident. According to the caller, the driver of the unit rolled over due to an unknown cause. The unit is hauling a hazardous, UN3257, Lytor 100 Tall Oil Resin, 9, PG III. Approximately 0.5-gallon of product has been released to the roadway from the dome lid. The caller indicated that they have personnel on site attempting to tighten the dome lid at this time. The caller also indicated that there is a possible diesel fuel and motor oil release. Local Fire and Police are on site at this time. Contractor indicated that there is a 1' x 1' area of the roadway that was impacted by the product. Approximately 0.5-gallon of product was released. Contractor indicated that the wrecker has up-righted the tanker at this time. Contractor also indicated that there is diesel fuel in a ditch. Contractor is trying to determine the amount released at this time.  Contractor indicated that the Fire Department estimates approximately 25-30 gallons of diesel fuel was released to the ditch line. Contractor indicated that the wrecker is taking the tanker back to their yard. Contractor indicated that the road has been re-opened and the truck has been removed from the site. Contractor indicated that the ditch and soil area has been impacted of an area of 20' x 25'. Contractor is using absorbent materials to clean the release at this timContractor has finished initial cleanup activities. Contractor has covered the impacted area with poly sheeting and absorbent booms until further remediation can be scheduled. Due to the location of the release, a lane closure will be needed. Contractor has generated (2) 55-gallon metal drums of impacted absorbent materials to be taken off site for disposal.

PACKAGE WAS PICKED UP FROM THE UNLOAD WALL AND AS UNLOADER STALEY WAS PLACING ONTO THE ROLLERS, THE SEAL ON BOTTOM OF THE PACKAGE FAILED AND THE CONTENTS FELL OUT OF THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX. THE CAP ON ONE BOTTLE OF THE ACETIC ACID CRACKED AND FAILED, SPILLING SOME OF THE ACETIC ACID ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER AND A COUPLE OF OTHER PACKAGES. THE FUMES RELEASED BY THE SPILL WERE VERY STRONG AND SMELLED OF VINEGAR. BECAUSE OF THE CONCENTRATION OF THE ACETIC ACID, THE IN HOUSE RESPONDERS COULD NOT GET CLOSE ENOUGH TO THE PACKAGE TO RESPOND DUE TO THE FUMES. THE CENTER FOLLOWED CHAIN OF COMMAND AND THE CENTER MANAGER CALLED P.E. TO HAVE AN OUTSIDE RESPONDER CALLED TO RESPOND TO THE SPILL. NO ONE CAME INTO DIRECT CONTACT WITH THE SPILLED ACID. UNLOADER EDLER HAD A FEW SMALL DROPS SPILL ONTO ONE BOOT AND SHE WASHED THIS OFF IN THE BATHROOM FLOOR SINK. ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIALS WERE CONSOLIDATED BY CLEAN HARBORS.
column169: THE OUTER PACKING WAS SOLID, BUT COULD HAVE BEEN BETTER TAPED TO PREVENT POSSIBLE FAILURE. THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX HAD A SMALL AMOUNT OF GLUE AND A SINGLE STRIP OF TAPE. MORE GLUE AND MORE TAPE COULD HAVE HELPED PREVENT FAILURE OF THE BOTTOM OF THE CARDBOARD BOX. IN ADDITION, THE INNER PACKAGING OF THE BOTTLES DID NOT HAVE ANY TYPE OF TAPE OR PROTECTION OVER THE BOTTLE TOPS TO PREVENT SPILLAGE IN THE CASE THAT THE BOTTLES WERE JOSTLED OR MOVED IN A WAY THAT COULD CAUSE THE CAPS TO BECOME LOOSE OR UNSECURED.

column168: On April 18, 2018, XPO Logistics (XJO Terminal) notified ERTS in regards to a hazardous, UN2920, Quaternary Ammonium Chloride, Ethanol, 8 (3), PG II (PRO#470445220) release. According to the caller, terminal personnel punctured (1) poly tote with a forklift on the dock. It is unknown in the amount released. Terminal personnel have contained the release at this time. Contractor advised that the tote is damaged from underneath releasing 30 gallons of material. He stated that the terminal had placed wood ships in a 20' radius to contain the release. ERTS instructed the contractor to make a containment area under the forklift as they perform a gravity transfer of the material. The will then clean the impacted area and cut up the damaged tote and containerize all the waste.  Contractor stated that they have generated 6-55 gallons poly drums.

column168: During routine facility inspection, a transport trailer was identified as having containers that had released in transit. column168: The Old Dominion tractor-trailer was traveling eastbound on US Highway 70, which is one lane in each direction. A pickup truck proceeding westbound crossed the centerline into the path of the Old Dominion tractor-trailer; the Old Dominion driver attempted to avoid the impact, but a head-on collision occurred, with the rear trailer becoming detached and coming to rest in the roadway whereas the tractor and the front trailer along with pickup truck both ended up off of the roadway on the north side where they caught fire. The Old Dominion driver was able to escape with some injury, and was transported by ambulance from the scene;  the driver of the pickup was fatally injured in the accident.  Several hours after the accident, during cleanup efforts by tow company personnel, the drum holding the hazardous material was punctured or otherwise breached resulting in dispersal of some of the material. The West Memphis Arkansas fire department responded to the hazardous materials call.

On April 19, 2018, XPO Logistics (XKK Terminal) notified ERTS in regards to a hazardous, UN1993, N-Serve 24, 3, PG III, (PRO#916993114) release. According to the caller, terminal personnel discovered (1) 330-gallon poly tote to be leaking on the dock. The caller indicated that the gasket looks to be worn. It is unknown in the amount released at this time. The caller indicated that the release is contained to the top of the tote.Contractor indicated that the tote was not leaking. The O-ring in the tote under the cap was not secure and the plug was not all the way closed. Contractor indicated that there was dried product on top of the tote, but it is not actively leaking. Contractor has secured the O-ring and fixed the plug.

column168: Our truck traveling E/B on Ziegler Blvd, a 4 lane divided roadway. Our vehicle was in left lane as right lanes ends and merges into the left lane just west of Athey Road. There were 2 vehicles behind us also in left lane. Another vehicle (see police accident report) tried to pass all vehicles in left lane before the right lane ended. He was unable to do so, he ran out of roadway and possible hit curb before he veered to the left and struck our vehicles tanker trailer in the center at the loading/unloading lines. The collision caused the external valve heads on the belly lines to be sheared off. This resulted in the lines from Compartment 1 and 2 (which were loaded) to release the product (gasoline) onto the roadway where it immediately ignited. (The other compartments were empty and the belly lines were dry) Our vehicle came to a stop in the roadway, the fire continued to burn and it appeared to have set the drive tires on the tractor on fire. The heat from the fire may have caused gasoline vapors to escape the trailer and also catch fire. Eventually Compartment #1 caught fire and burned thru the shell at top. Compartment #2 did not burn and product in it was not lost. Only product in Compartment #1 was lost due to the fire. The product in that compartment did not spill onto the ground, it just burned while being contained in the trailer. The only product that was actually lost onto the ground was that which was in the wet belly lines of Compartment #1 & 2. That product was also burned off.
column169: Accident was not the fault of our truck driver. The other vehicle was carless/reckless in his actions and caused the accident.

column168: RESPONDED TO A PACKAGE THAT HAD A STRANGE ODOR AT STALL 322. THE PACKAGE HAD NO SIGNS OF SPILLAGE BUT A STRONG ODOR THAT AFFECTED THE HYDRION PAPER. TWO ORM-D AND ONE LEAKING BOTTLE OF JOHNSEN'S MOBILE A/C REFRIGERANT FREEZE COMPLETE A/C SYSTEM FLUSH WAS FOUND. THE JOHNSEN'S MOBILE A/C REFRIGERANT FREEZE COMPLETE A/C SYSTEM FLUSH WAS LEAKING ONTO A BOX INSIDE OF THE MAIN BOX.
column169: DECLARE HAZMAT AND PACK BETTER SO THE CONTENTS DO NOT CRUSH THE HAZMAT.

column168: PART VI – DESCRIPTION OF EVENTS & PACKAGE FAILURE: AN EAST PENN DRIVER ARRIVED AT HIS DESTINATION TO UNLOAD PRODUCT WITH THE CUSTOMER. WHEN HE EXITED THE TRUCK HE SMELLED SOMETHING BURNING. WHEN THE DRIVER OPENED THE REAR DOOR OF THE TRAILER HE SAW SMOKED AND FLAMES IN THE FRONT NOSE OF THE TRAILER. IT WAS TOO SMOKY FOR THE DRIVER TO THE ENTER THE TRAILER TO TRY AND EXTINGUISH THE FIRE WITHOUT PROPER PROTECTIVE GEAR. THE CUSTOMER SAW WHAT WAS HAPPENING AND CALLED 911. THE DRIVER MADE SURE THE TRAILER WAS AT A SAFE DISTANCE FROM ANY STRUCTURES AND ROADWAY AND UNHOOKED THE TRAILER FROM THE TRUCK/TRACTOR, TO GIVE EMERGENCY PERSONNEL ENOUGH ROOM TO ACCESS THE TRAILER.  AETNA HOOK HOSE & LADDER AND THE DNREC ARRIVED AT THE SCENE. A BERM WAS PUT AROUND A STORM DRAIN TO PREVENT SULFURIC ACID AND LEAD FOR ENTERING THE DRAIN. THE FIRE WAS PUT OUT AND THE NON-DAMAGED BATTERIES WERE REMOVED. THE DNREC CALLED FOR A CLEAN-UP COMPANY, GUARDIAN ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES TO HELP WITH THE CLEAN-UP. GUARDIAN RE-ESTABLISHED THE BERM AND PUT DOWN SODA ASH ON THE PAVEMENT TO NEUTRALIZE THE ACID FROM THE BATTERIES WHILE PUTTING OUT THE FIRE. ONCE THE FIRE WAS OUT THEY TOOK OUT THE REMAINING BATTERIES. THE GOOD, UNDAMAGED BATTERIES WERE SEPARATED FROM THE DAMAGED ONES. THE BURNT DAMAGED BATTERIES WERE BAGGED AND DRUMMED TO BE RETURNED BACK TO EAST PENN MANUFACTURING CO., TO BE RECYCLED/RECLAIMED IN OUR SECONDARY LEAD SMELTER. DRUMS OF CLEAN UP DEBRIS AND PPE, AND A DRUM OF SPENT LIQUID WATER/ACID MIX ARE BEING TESTED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  THE CAUSE OF THE FIRE WAS A SKID OF LARGE BATTERIES ARRANGED WITH THE TERMINAL POSTS TOWARD THE CENTER. A DIRECT CONTACT CAUSED A CLOSED CIRCUIT AND SHORTENED 2 BATTERIES FACING EACH OTHER. THE IGNITION WAS EXTREME ENOUGH TO MELT THE LEAD AND START THE CARBOARD IN-BETWEEN THE LAYERS AND POSTS FIRE.
column169: PART VII – RECOMMENDATIONS/ACTIONS TAKEN TO PREVENT RECURRENC: TAILGATES WITH THE PRODUCTION PERSONNEL ON THE IMPORTANCE OF UTILIZING THE POST PROTECTORS AND PLACEMENT OF “HONEYCOMB” CARDBOARD BETWEEN TERMINALS WILL BE REVIEWED. VISUAL AIDS WILL ALSO BE MADE TO SHOW HOW TO PROPERLY PALLETIZE THIS STYLE BATTERY.

column168: First I greatly apologize as this is past the 30 day window and is fully my responsibility.  When looking in our record keeping system I accidentally looked at the date I closed the file versus the date of incident and wrote that down as my due date.    • The fill line comes through a wall and is angled at a 45 degree angle.  Driver has to fight/drag with the hose to get it hooked up.   o Note when he removed their cap from their fill line initially there was some product there.  Roughly enough to fil up the inside of the cap.   • There is a type of gate valve on our side but nothing that clicks or locks into place. • One person was with him the entire time and there was another person up by the tank which is 5 stories up.  The guy with him and the guy upstairs have walkie talkies.   • At the end the driver confirmed with the guy upstairs that he is completely closed down and ready for disconnect.  He confirmed everything was shut down.   • Driver walked the hose to the customers fill line and shut the valve.  He could tell the hose was light.  They watched him walk the hose.   • He opened the bleeder valve and let all air and product come out into his bucket that would. • Driver had to work it a little bit to get it unhooked and when it gave way the hose popped off like it had a good amount of pressure and he did get product on him.   • This was a burst of product.  It did not keep running out.   • It wasn’t until he showered that it ran down inside his chemical suit as he showered the first time (5-6 minutes).  When he realized it was getting in his suit he started removing PPE and then jumped back in the shower for 20-30 minutes • Bleeder valve on our trailer seemed to operate normally and was not loose.  It shouldn’t be gummed up with product as most are just cleaners.   • There are 3 valves on the entire customer set up.  One where we hook up, then one on the other side of the wall before the fill line goes up the 5 stories (which we’re not allowed access to), and then one up by the tank 5 stories up.   We think that the valve closest to him isn’t holding or wasn’t fully closed allowing trapped pressurized product between the two valves to spray out.  The first valve on the other side of the wall, valve prior to the piping going vertically must not have been holding.   • Josh was then taken to then transported for treatment.  He was treated and released and has made a full recovery.
column169: We submitted a formal request for the customer to inspect their valves to ensure they are holding.  We also flagged this on delivery with a driver who has been there before and that this will be completed on first shift hours as the person helping unload wasn't there at that time.

column168: PART VI-DESCRIPTION OF EVENTS AND PACKAGE FAILURE. THE KENAN TRANSPORT, LLC DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO DELIVER GASOLINE INTO THE CUSTOMER’S STORAGE TANK. IN THE COURSE OF DOING SO, HE MISTAKENLY OPENED A VALVE ON THE TRAILER PRIOR TO CONNECTING THE HOSE TO THE STORAGE TANK. AS A RESULT, APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF GASOLINE WAS RELEASED. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND HANDLED THE REMEDIATION. NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS ANTICIPATED.
column169: PART VII- RECOMMENDATIONS/ACTION TAKEN TO PREVENT RECURRENCE.  KENAN TRANSPORT, LLC WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND ENFORCE SAFE LOADING/UNLOADING POLICIES AND PROCEDURES.

column168: PART VI-DESCRIPTION OF EVENTS AND PACKAGE FAILURE THE TRANSPORT SERVICE, LLC DRIVER NOTICED A SLOW LEAK COMING FROM THE TRAILER. ES&H ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND HANDLED THE REMEDIATION. THE LOAD WAS SAFELY TRANSFERRED INTO ANOTHER TRAILER WITHOUT INCIDENT. NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS ANTICIPATED.

column168: Around 6:35 AM on 4/24/18, an Austin Powder Company vehicle (2006 Mack Multi-Purpose Bulk Truck) left the company facility in Blountsville, AL.  It was traveling southbound on Rocky Hollow Rd, which is a 2 lane asphalt roadway around 6:45 AM.  The truck was at roughly 41 MPH, complying with the speed limit of 45. The truck was loaded with hazard class 5.1 ammonium nitrate in a DOT specification cargo tank, and 5.1 ammonium nitrate in 3 non-spec cargo bins.  It also contained a tank with roughly 200 gallons of fuel oil # 2 (for producing blended products).  About 10 minutes into the trip, the truck began veering off the right side of the road.  The driver claims that he was putting down a lift axle on the vehicle, which requires reaching over to engage a lever on the dashboard.  He slowed down slightly when doing this.   When he felt the truck pull to the right, the driver's response was to steer to the left in attempt to get the truck back on the roadway.  The right hand side wheels dug deep into the soil at the edge of the pavement, causing the truck to pitch violently to the right.  The truck's body made contact with the ditch and rolled, sliding a short distance down the road, and coming to rest mostly off the road on its drivers side.  The lids were ripped off the 3 ammonium nitrate bins, causing about 5,000 pounds of the granular substance to form in a pile.  Roughly 100 pounds of ammonium nitrate emulsion was expelled out of the pressure relief valve on the top of the tank.  The fuel oil tank was punctured with a  basketball-sized hole, causing roughly 150 gallons of the product fuel to leak out.  The driver extricated himself from the wrecked truck, and initiated Austin's emergency response procedure.  The driver was transported to the hospital where he was treated for non-life threatening injuries (bruises, cuts, scrapes).  The spilled product was confined to a relatively small area that can be described as grassy pasture.  The spill contractor removed the spilled product and the impacted soil, placing it in 4 roll-off containers.  From there, it was profiled, and landfilled.  The road re-opened for traffic around 11:00 AM.
column169: The 200 gallon diesel tank failed because of a large hole being punctured in it.  We cannot recommend any improvements to the packaging.  Nor can we with the DOT specification cargo tank containing the AN emulsion.  The product that spilled, was simply "burped" out of the pressure relief vent at the top of the tank due to the sideways orientation of the truck.  The majority of the product that spilled was ammonium nitrate, which simply fell from the 3 bins when their covers were ripped off.  In the case of the packaging, if anything failed, it was the closure on the AN bins.  We have found in the past however, that even when they initially stay closed in an accident, we still end up losing product in that they are not designed to be sealed packages.  The driver was new to the company (not new to driving).  He had recently undergone our extensive driver candidate training as well as our on-the-job training, which includes driving with an already qualified driver for a minimum amount of hours (in his case 8).  We required this driver to do the on-the-job portion of his training all over again prior to dispatching him alone. Because of this accident, we have examined our policy on using lift axles.  We found that there was some misunderstanding on the part of our driver group at this facility on when to engage them (in this case, the driver engaged the lift axles a few minutes into the trip for reasons unknown).  We have gone back to all drivers and instructed them to engage lift axles in the lot of the Austin facility prior to leaving on their trip.  This will potentially eliminate a distraction in the cab of the vehicle, and ensure that the truck is not overweight.

column168: A Refinery Specialties Inc. (RSI) driver was hauling seven (7) IBC's of specialty oilfield chemicals on a flat bed trailer from RSI's Ft. Stockton yard to a customer O&G lease site (Pecan/Woods State Unit) near Coyanosa, Pecos County, Texas. At approximately 7:25 AM CST the driver turned off of Highway 290 into the Love's truck stop located at 2723 E. US Highway 290 in Ft. Stockton, Pecos County, Texas. As the driver made the turn, one of the totes slid off the back of the trailer and struck the ground. The force of the impact crushed the metal cage and ruptured the plastic container, causing a roughly 6" tear along the center top edge of the container (see photos). This resulted in the almost instantaneous release of the IBC's contents, roughly 300 gallons of a xylene-ethylbenzene solvent blend (RSI-3119-164-106). A Safety Data Sheet (SDS) for this product was submitted to Mr. Galata Tona of US DOT on April 27, 2018, by way of follow-up to a phone conversation between Karl Mueller, RSI's Environmental Manager and Mr. Tona earlier that day. Mr. Justin Owns of RSI and the driver (Mr. Jaime Palcios) initiated response actions and worked with truck stop staff to re-direct traffic and attempted to contain the spill using clay absorbent until Fire Department/HAZMAT teams could arrive. Units from Department of Public Safety (DPS), local police, and local fire department (Ft. Stockton VFD) responded to the incident; the driver was cited for failure to properly secure load. At 9:10 AM ET Love's contacted their national spill response contractor, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS), who then dispatched a local sub-contractor (Accuworx) to conduct spill response/remediation operations. ERTS also made initial local, county, state, and federal notifications. Upon arrival at the scene, Accuworx technicians removed ponded free liquids from concrete and other impervious surfaces, followed by application of clay absorbent and sweeping of impacted impervious areas. Approximately 4-5 drums of impacted soil, along with another 2-3 drums of impacted sorbent and spill debris was generated as a result of response activities and transferred to a roll-off box for disposal. Final invoices and manifests for disposal have yet to be received, and a final report summarizing the response is delayed pending receipt of same.
column169: RSI drivers have been counseled/reminded of the need to properly inspect loads and trucks/trailers as part of pre-trip inspection process, and use of a pre-trip inspection checklist has been proposed. Clarification that load preparation and securement is the driver's responsibility has been communicated throughout the company.

column168: HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INCIDENT REPORT – PART VI K2 TANK LINES INC. DATE OF INCIDENT: 4-23-18  K2 TANK LINES WAS NOT AWARE OF A POSSIBLE ACCIDENT UNTIL AT LEAST 8 HOURS AFTER OCCURRENCE. ANOTHER DRIVER CALLED DISPATCH AROUND 12:00 SAYING HE THOUGHT HE HEARD ON THE NEWS THE NAME OF A K2 DRIVER AS THE NEWS REPORT DISCUSSED THE LARGE TRUCK FIRE ON I-70. IT WAS SEVERAL HOURS LATER THAT K2 CONFIRMED THE IDENTITY OF THE EQUIPMENT AND DRIVER INVOLVED.  WE HAVE NOT BEEN ABLE TO LOCATE AN EYEWITNESS TO THESE EVENTS AND THE DRIVER INVOLVED CLAIMS TO NOT HAVE MEMORY OF THE SPECIFIC DETAILS. THIS IS A SUMMARY OF WHAT WE HAVE BEEN ABLE TO DETERMINE.  ON 4-23-18, AT ABOUT 4:00 AM, DRIVER WAS EASTBOUND ON I-70 IN ST. PETERS, MO AND APPARENTLY LOST CONTROL STRIKING THE GUARDRAIL. THIS CAUSED HIM TO OVERTURN ON THE RAMP/ACCESS ROAD. HE WAS DRIVING A TANKER TRAILER WITH 8,501 GALLONS OF ETHANOL, AND WHEN EMERGENCY PERSONNEL ARRIVED, THEY ALLOWED IT TO BURN OUT. DUE TO THE SIZE OF THE FIRE, THE EQUIPMENT WAS COMPLETELY DESTROYED AND ITS ACTUAL IDENTITY AND OWNERSHIP WAS NOT DETERMINED UNTIL THE EVENING OF 4-23-18.  THE MISSOURI STATE POLICE CALLED THE STATE OF MISSOURI DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES TO THE SCENE VERY QUICKLY, AND THEY ENGAGED A COMPANY (ENVIRONMENTAL RESTORATIONS) TO CONTAIN ANY SPILL AND MONITOR THE SCENE. NONE OF THE ETHANOL REACHED ANY POND OR STREAM, AND REMEDIATION OF THE DIRT/GRASS AREA AROUND THE SCENE BEGAN IMMEDIATELY. K2 WAS NOT AWARE OF THIS UNTIL THE NEXT DAY. SOME SKIMMING OF DIRT WAS REQUIRED ALONGSIDE THE ROADWAY. THE MO DNR AGREED THAT THE REMEDIATION OPERATIONS COULD CEASE BY THE NEXT DAY. IT IS ESTIMATED THAT THE TOTAL INVOICE FROM ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDATION WILL BE $35,000 TO $40,000.  PROPERTY DAMAGE TO THE ROAD WAS INCLUDED 2 LIGHT POLES, GUARDRAILS, CONCRETE MEDIAN BARRIES AND ROAD SURFACE. THE STATE OF MISSOURI WAS REPAIRING ALL DAMAGE AND THE ACTUAL COST IS UNKNOWN. WE DO NOT HAVE ANY PICTURES OF THE INCIDENT AS THE DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL WITH MINOR INJURIES AND WE WERE NOT AWARE OF IT UNTIL CLEAN-UP HAD BEGUN. WE WERE ABLE TO FIND SOME ST. LOUIS TV NEW COVERAGE SHOWING THE FIRE.
column169: WITHOUT KNOWLEDGE OF THE ACTUAL EVENTS THAT LED TO THIS ACCIDENT, K2 TANK LINES IS ENHANCING OUR ONGOING TRAINING FOR ALL DRIVERS IN AREAS THAT POSSIBLY COULD HAVE CONTRIBUTED TO THIS EVENT.

column42: AMMONIUM NITRATE, WITH NOT MORE THAN 0.2%  OF COMBUSTIBLE MATERIALS, INCLUDING ANY ORGANIC SUBSTANCE CALCULATED AS CARBON TO THE EXCLUSION OF ANY OTHER ADDED SUBSTANCE
column168: Around 6:45 AM on 4/25/18, a multi-purpose bulk truck (MBT) containing ammonium nitrate, ammonium nitrate emulsion, and fuel oil #2 left out of Austin Powder's facility at 4487 Troy Hawk Run Rd. Philipsburg, PA.  The truck was headed for a customer in Karthaus, PA.  The road, which is known as State Hwy 53, or Kylertown Drifting Road, is a 2 lane state route that is relatively narrow, with a small berm of roughly 3'.  The speed limit is 45 where the accident occurred. The road conditions  were wet.  About 10-15 minutes into the trip, the truck was traveling around a  curve  (going to the left).  After going around the curve, the vehicle began veering off the roadway.  The driver attempted to bring the vehicle back onto the road by steering to the left causing the truck to overturn and roll.  The truck slid for roughly 70 feet where it came to rest in the roadway facing east at the edge of a farmer's field.  The truck was blocking both lanes of traffic.  The vehicle came to rest on its passenger side at a telephone poll, which was cracked and bent by the impact. With the truck on its side, ammonium nitrate began slowly leaking out of the 2 cargo bins (the lids of the bids had been torn off in the crash).  Fuel Oil #2, which was also present on the unit, leaked from its tank, which had been damaged.  In total about 1000 pounds of ammonium nitrate and 100-150 gallons of fuel oil spilled from the vehicle.   There was also a DOT specification cargo tank on the vehicle containing 920 gallons of ammonium nitrate emulsion.  This tank was not damaged in the event, and no product was released. The driver extricated himself from the vehicle under his own power, and refused medical treatment at the scene (he later was taken to the hospital for an evaluation and post-accident drug screen.  He was found to have non-life threatening injuries).  The driver was able to initiate Austin's emergency response plan, so first responders were on the scene within a few minutes. A spill contactor showed up a short time after that, and used a vacuum truck to remove the product from the roadway and field.  Two large rolloff containers were filled with the spilled product, and taken back to the Austin facility.  A crew replaced the telephone pole, and the roadway was re-opened completely around 1:00 PM.  The impacted area of the field was covered with plastic, and further remediation was done at a later date, generating 18 tons of impacted soil that was profiled and landfilled.
column169: The driver was experienced, having operated a MBT for Austin for the last several years.  He frequently drove this section of road as there are 2 customers that require taking this portion of route 53.  The driver was interviewed the following day, and indicated that he swerved to avoid deer that he claims were in the roadway.  The driver claims to have been traveling around 35 MPH. However the telematics equipment on the vehicle did not capture second by second data prior to the event, so we are largely unable to tell.  Whether he was indeed swerving to avoid an animal or he took the curve too fast and was unable to stay on the road, the result is clearly that he left the roadway for a distance of about 200 feet, struggled to get back on it, and overturned the truck.  This particular section of State Route 53 is well known to our drivers in the area, and through our discussions with drivers and our observations at the scene, we have decided to route the drivers a different way when servicing these customers in the future.  We have a policy of not swerving to avoid animals when driving a CMV.  This policy is being reinforced with our driver group.  Lastly, this driver is on light duty work because of his injuries.  If he is retained, he will undergo extensive retraining and evaluation prior to getting back in a CMV.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: On April 25, 2018, Expeditors Atlanta Branch (“Expeditors-ATL”) received documentation and cargo from freight forwarder, Log’Xpress International for a shipment to Lockheed Martin (“the consignee”). A review of the documentation, which detailed predominately aircraft parts, also included a proforma commercial invoice for a “Charged Sphere Fire Extinguisher.”  Since this commodity was suspected of containing Dangerous Goods (“DG”), Expeditors-ATL contacted the consignee and requested additional information.  On April 26, 2018, the consignee, confirmed that the “Charged Sphere Fire Extinguisher” contained DG.   At this time, Expeditors-ATL informed the consignee that the DG commodity would require re-packaging, labeling and preparation of a Shipper’s Dangerous Goods declaration.    On May 08, 2018, Expeditors-ATL was informed by the consignee, that Propack International would create the dangerous goods declaration and repackage the DG item to bring it into compliance with the DG regulations. Expeditors-ATL communicated this information to St. George warehouse, the location where the cargo was being stored.    On May 11, 2018, Propack International was dispatched to St. George warehouse where they recovered the DG item and returned it to their warehouse facility to perform repackaging and documentation services.      On May 15, 2018, once the shipment was properly packaged and documented, the shipment was delivered back to Expeditors-ATL for subsequent delivery to the consignee.
column169: Expeditors-ATL contacted freight forward Log'Xpress and informed them of the undeclared dangerous good issue.  Consignee Lockheed Martin was also contacted and informed about the undeclared commodity incident and their responsibility to bring the shipment into compliance with the DG regulations to include repacking, labeling and preparation of the DG Shipper's Declaration.

Original comments:  While a package handler was loading the trailer, they noticed a wet/leaking package and informed their manager.  The manager quickly informed QA of the situation they had in their area.  QA grabbed a red tote, lined it with a clear hazmat bag and grabbed loose absorb.  They rushed over to the area to investigate the situation.  Upon arrival, they noticed the package in question was leaking the barcode stated hazmat and placed it in the tote.  QA cleaned up the area with the loose absorb and brought the package back to QA placing it in the hazmat processing cage.  The shipper did not have any diamond labels nor OP900 on the out side of this package.  The shipper stated in f track that the substance inside was the following:   Corrosive liquids, n.o.s Technical Name:  (DISODIUM METASILICATE)  UN1760  Packaging Group:  III  New Comments:

column168: WHILE OFFLOADING FLIGHT 522 ON 21 APRIL, THE WIND BLEW A BOX CONTAINING 250 UCI OF ABSCISIC ACID A CARBON 14 TRACER OFF THE CARGOVEYOR AND ONTO THE AIRPORT RAMP. A COMPANY VEHICLE WAS PASSING NEAR AND RAN OVER THE BOX CRUSHING IT AND TEARING IT OPEN BY MAKING A HOLE IN ONE CORNER OF THE BOX. THE BOX DID NOT APPEAR LEAKING BUT DID CONTAIN ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO ABSORB ANY SPILLED MATERIAL. THE BOX WAS MOVED TO THE CARGO FACILITY WHERE IT WAS QUARANTINED. UPON NOTIFICATION THE NEXT MORNING, THE PHL AIRPORT AUTHORITY RESPONDED TO THE CARGO FACILITY AND MEASURED THE AREA AROUND THE PACKAGE FOR EXCESSIVE RADIOACTIVITY. ONLY BACKGROUND RADIOACTIVITY WAS MEASURED. THE BOX WAS MOVED TO A SMALL STEEL CONTAINMENT DRUM WHERE IT REMAINED UNTIL IT WAS PICKED UP THE FOLLOWING MONDAY MORNING TO BE REPACKAGED. THE DAMAGED PACKAGE WAS PROPERLY REPACKAGED FOR TRANSPORT AS A UN2910 RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, EXCEPTED PACKAGE-LIMITED QUANTITY OF MATERIAL. THE PACKAGED WAS PICKED UP MAY 1 BY YRC TRUCKING AND TRANSPORTED BACK TO THE SHIPPER, ARC IN SAINT LOUIS. THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF MATERIAL. THE INNER PACKAGE CONTAINING THE AMINO ACID WITH THE CARBON 14 REMAINED INTACT.
column169: THIS WAS AN UNAVOIDABLE ACCIDENT DUE TO WEATHER CONDITIONS. PERSONNEL MAY HAVE BEEN MORE CAREFUL HAD THEY THOUGHT OF THE WEIGHT PACKAGE AND THE STRENGTH OF THE WIND AT THE TIME. UNKNOWN WHAT OTHER MITIGATING MEASURES THERE MIGHT BE.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. TRACTOR-TANKER UNTIL WAS RUN OFF THE ROAD RESULTING IN A ROLL-OVER AND TRACTOR FIRE. AS A RESULT OF THE ROLL-OVER THE TANKER WAS DAMAGED AND RELEASED APPROXIMATELY 4,200 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL. THE SOUTH CAROLINA DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION AND SEVERAL FIRE DEPARTMENTS AND POLICE DEPARTMENTS RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT. JBR ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (JBR) WAS CONTACTED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. JBR INSPECTED THE SITE AND DISCOVERED IMPACTED SOIL AREA APPROXIMATELY 600 FEET LONG AND UP TO 10 FEET WIDE. DIESEL FUEL THEN RUNS OFF OF THE SCDOT RIGHT AWAY APPROXIMATELY 800 FEET AND INTO A PASTURE. JBR UTILIZED VAC TRUCKS TO RECOVER OILY WATER FROM THE TRENCHES AND SUMPS IN THE DITCH LINE. JBR COORDINATED DISPOSAL OF THE WASTE GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT.
column169: SINCE THE RELEASE WAS ACCIDENTAL, NO PLANS CURRENTLY EXIST TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. HOWEVER, KC TRANSPORT, INC. WILL CONTINUE TO REINFORCE SAFETY GUIDELINES AND HANDLING PROCEDURES TO ALL PERSONNEL.

column168: ON APRIL 23, 2018, AT APPROXIMATELY 2:25 P.M. CDT, A TRACTOR-TRAILER WAS TRAVELING AT THE ABOVE-REFERENCED LOCATION WHEN THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF THE TRACTOR-TRAILRE, ROLLING THE UNIT OVER ONTO IT’S SIDE. AS A RESULT, SIX (6) OF THE CARGO’S 13 275-GALLON TOTES OF THPS BECAME DAMAGED. THE DAMAGE IS DESCRIBED AS THE PLASTIC BODY OF THE 275-GALLON TOTES AND THE PRESSURE RELEASE VALVE BECOMING DAMAGED RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 70 GALLONS OF THPS FROM THE TRAILER INTERIOR TO THE ASPHALT SURFACES OF THE ROADWAY AND ADJACENT SOIL SURFACES. A CREW FROM SUNPRO SPECIALTY SERVICES ARRIVED ON-SITE. SUNPRO PERSONNEL UTILIZED MACHINERY TO OFFLOAD 13 275-GALLON TOTES FROM THE TRAILER INDIVIDUALLY FOR INSPECTION. THE CREW THEN TRANSFERRED THE THPS FROM SIX (6) DAMAGED 275-GALLON TOTES INTO SIX (6) 275-GALLON TOTES BROUGHT TO SITE. SUNPRO PERSONNEL THEN UTILIZED A PUMP TO COLLECT THPS FROM AREAS OF POOLING AROUND THE TRAILER AND A CONTAINMENT POOL DEPLOYED BY THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT. SUNPRO PERSONNEL DEPLOYED GRANULAR ABSORBENTS TO THE INTERIOR OF THE TRAILER AND WORKED IN WITH HAND TOOLS. THE CREW THEN DEPLOYED GRANULAR ABSORBENTS ONTO THE THPS AND DIESEL FUEL-IMPACTED ASPHALT SURFACES AND WORKED IN WITH HAND TOOLS. SUNPRO PERSONNEL COLLECTED THE THPS-IMPACTED MATERIAL FOR TRANSPORT AND DISPOSAL.
column169: ADDITIONAL DRIVERS TRAINING.

column168: THIS UNLABELED AND UNMARKED SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED DURING THE TRANSIT WHEN IT WAS NOTICED WHEN IT WAS BEING SCANNED BY PERSONNEL. THE SHIPMENT WAS QUESTIONED BY THOSE PARTIES THERE, AND WITH ME, AS I WAS NOT FAMILIAR WITH THIS SHIPMENT WHICH IS UNDECLARED AND SHOULD NOT BE TRANSPORTED BY AIR. REGRETFULLY THIS DID MOVE VIA AN AIRCRAFT, BUT NOT A FEDEX AIRCRAFT TO THIS LOCATION. THIS SHIPMENT INCLUDED 2 DRESSES(100% COTTON) AND SOME HOMEMADE FOOD AND HOMEMADE SNACKS. COPRA IS THE DRIED MEAT OR KERNEL OF THE COCONUT, WHICH IS THE FRUIT OF THE COCONUT PALM. THAT IS WHAT WAS NOTICED DURING THEIR SCAN. THE STATION THAT REPORTED THE INCIDENT FAILED TO CALL TO REPORT THIS INCIDENT AND AFTER A COUPLE DAYS OF EMAILS, I TURNED IT OVER TO THE FAA ON 4-27-2018 AT 10:30 AM. A NOTIFICATION,& PHOTOS WERE SUBMITTED TO THEM. THE SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD FOR DISPOSAL. ,

column168: ODYSSEY TANKER DRIVER WAS FILLING 2,582 GALLON DOUBLE-WALLED SODIUM HYPOCHLANT STORAGE TANK AT CITY OF OCALA WATER TREATMENT PLANT. TANK LEVEL SENSOR FAILED TOWARD END OF EVOLUTION AND TANK OVERFLOWED AND 80 GALLONS FROM VENT ONTO GROUND BEFORE EVOLUTION STOPPED. SPILL AREA WAS CLEANED UP AND SOIL SAMPLES TAKEN WITH FOUR HOURS SHOWED NO EVIDENCE OF A SPILL. BASED ON PH TEST OF SOIL, WE BELIEVE INITIAL REPORT OF 80 GALLONS WAS SIGNIFICANTLY EXAGGERATED AND FIND SPILL VOLUME CLOSER TO 10 GALLONS. LEVEL SENSING DEVICE WAS REPAIRED TO PREVENT RECURRENCE.
column169: LEVEL SENSING DEVICE WAS REPAIRED TO PREVENT RECURRENCE.

column168: On 4/16/18 at approximately 11:15 am a Transport Services tanker truck was in the process of receiving a load of Ethyl Acrylate at IMTT. With approximately 150 gallons on the truck the IMTT Chemical Operator discovered a drip on flange between the truck's internal and external valve. The IMTT Chemical Operator immediately stopped the loading operation and contacted his supervisor. The IMTT Chemical Supervisor arrived at the scene and surveyed the situation. The IMTT Chemical Supervisor instructed the IMTT Chemical Operator to blow the loading hose back into the truck trailer. After speaking with the customer of the product being loaded the decision was made to pump off the balance of the product from the truck trailer back to the original above ground storage tank.
column169: IMTT contacted the customer of the product being loaded to inform them of the incident.  The customer will follow up with the transportation company regarding any mechanical issues with the truck or related  components.

column168: EMPLOYEE NAME: CHRIS HOCKLEY DATE: 4/2/2018 TIME: APPROXIMATELY 1:45 PM LOCATION: HWY 7 ¾ MILE OUTSIDE MEEKER, CO  PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT BEING USED: SEAT BELT  DESCRIPTION OF INCIDENT: WHILE TRAVELING TO MEEKER, COLORADO FOR A FRAC-WATER HEATING JOB, MR. CHRIS HOCKLEY, STATED HE WAS TRAVELING AT THE POSTED SPEED OF 50 MPH WHERE HE DROPPED THE PASSENGER SIDE WHEEL OFF OF THE ROAD SIDE EDGE OF HWY 64 OUTSIDE OF MEEKER, CO. AND WAS PULLED OFF OF THE SIDE OF THE ROADWAY INTO A FIELD WHICH BROKE THE PROPANE TRAILER OFF OF THE TRACTOR CAUSING THE TRAILER TO ROLL OVER. NO PERSONNEL INJURIES OR PROPANE WAS RELEASE. THE DESCENT WAS APPROXIMATELY 8 FEET FROM THE ROADWAY TO THE FIELD LEVEL. MR. HOCKEY WAS WEARING HIS SEAT BELT AND WAS NOT INJURED. THE PROPANE TRAILER BROKE OFF AT THE KING PIN PLATE, WHICH REMAINED ATTACHED TO THE TRACTOR FIFTH WHEEL. THE TRACTOR DRIVE LINE, AND DRIVE AXLES WERE BROKEN AND DAMAGED BEYOND REPAIR. THE PROPANE TRAILER FENDER WELLS WERE DEMOLISHED AND THE TRAILING AXLES WERE BROKEN BEYOND REPAIR. THE INTEGRITY OF THE TRAILER TANK WAS NOT DAMAGED BEYOND PAINT BEING SMUDGED FROM ROLLING OVER AND INITIALLY STRIKING THE TRACTOR DRIVE TIRES ON THE DESCENT.    IMMEDIATE CAUSE: DRIVER MANEUVERED THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER TOO CLOSE TO THE ROADSIDE EDGE AND DROPPED THE VEHICLE AND TRAILER OFF AN EMBANKMENT, LEAVING THE PAVED PORTION OF THE ROADWAY ENDING UP IN A FIELD AND ROLLED THE PROANE TRAILER.
column169: IMMEDIATE CONTROLS: DRIVER NEEDS TO ENSURE PROPER DISTANCE FROM THE ROADWAY EDGE IS MAINTAINED AT ALL TIMES.   CONTRIBUTING CAUSES: NO APPARENT CONTIBUTING CAUSES TO THIS ACCIDENT. WEATHER WAS DRY, THERE WERE NO APPROACHING VEHICLES ON THE ROAD AT THE TIME IN THIS INCIDENT. THE WIND WAS GUSTING HIGH APPROXIMATELY 20-30 MPH, BUT THE DRIVER STATED HE DID NOT FEEL THE WIND PUSHING THE VEHICLES, NOR THAT THE WIND CAUSED THE ACCIDENT.   CONTRIBUTING CONTROLS:  ROOT CAUSE: DRIVER WAS DRIVING AT ABOUT 50-MPH (WHICH WAS THE POSTED ROAD SPEED), AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT, BUT WITH THE NARROW ROADWAY AND WITH NO ROADWAY SHOULDERS IN THAT ROAD SECTION, THE 50-MPH SPEED WAS TOO FAST FOR THAT PARTICULAR SECTION OF THE ROADWAY.   ROOT CONTROLS: DRIVERS SHALL REDUCE THEIR VEHICLE SPEED TO A SAFE FOR ALL EXISTING CONDITIONS ANYTIME THEY ARE OPERATING LSI COMPANY VEHICLES.

column168: On 4/16/18 at approximately 11:15 am a Transport Services tanker truck was in the process of receiving a load of Ethyl Acrylate at IMTT. With approximately 150 gallons on the truck the IMTT Chemical Operator discovered a drip on flange between the truck's internal and external valve. The IMTT Chemical Operator immediately stopped the loading operation and contacted his supervisor. The IMTT Chemical Supervisor arrived at the scene and surveyed the situation. The IMTT Chemical Supervisor instructed the IMTT Chemical Operator to blow the loading hose back into the truck trailer. After speaking with the customer of the product being loaded the decision was made to pump off the balance of the product from the truck trailer back to the original above ground storage tank.
column169: IMTT contacted the customer of the product being loaded to inform them of the incident. The customer will follow up with the transportation company regarding any mechanical issues with the truck or related components.

column168: AN EAST PENN DRIVER ARRIVED AT HIS DESTINATION TO UNLOAD PRODUCT WITH THE CUSTOMER. WHEN HE EXITED THE TRUCK HE SMELLED SOMETHING BURNING. WHEN THE DRIVER OPENED THE REAR DOOR OF THE TRAILER HE SAW SMOKE AND FLAMES IN THE FRONT NOSE OF THE TRAILER. IT WAS TOO SMOKY FOR THE DRIVER TO ENTER THE TRAILER TO TRY AND EXTINGUISH THE FIRE WITHOUT PROPER PROTECTIVE GEAR. THE CUSTOMER SAW WHAT WAS HAPPENING AND CALLED 911. THE DRIVER MADE SURE THE TRAILER WAS AT A SAFE DISTANCE FROM ANY STRUCTURES AND ROADWAY AND UNHOOKED THE TRAILER FROM THE TRUCK/TRACTOR, TO GIVE EMERGENCY PERSONNEL ENOUGH ROOM TO ACCESS THE TRAILER.  AETNA HOOK HOSE & LADDER AND THE DNREC ARRIVED AT THE SCENE. A BERM WAS PUT AROUND A STORM DRAIN TO PREVENT SULFURIC ACID AND LEAD FOR ENTERING THE DRAIN. THE FIRE WAS PUT OUT AND THE NON-DAMAGED BATTERIES WERE REMOVED. THE DNREC CALLED FOR A CLEAN-UP COMPANY, GUARDIAN ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES TO HELP WITH THE CLEAN-UP. GUARDIAN RE-ESTABLISHED THE BERM AND PUT DOWN SODA ASH ON THE PAVEMENT TO NEUTRALIZE THE ACID FROM THE BATTERIES WHILE PUTTING OUT THE FIRE. ONCE THE FIRE WAS OUT THEY TOOK OUT THE REMAINING BATTERIES. THE GOOD, UNDAMAGED BATTERIES WERE SEPARATED FROM THE DAMAGED ONES. THE BURNT DAMAGED BATTERIES WERE BAGGED AND DRUMMED TO BE RETURNED BACK TO EAST PENN MANUFACTURING CO., TO BE RECYCLED/RECLAIMED IN OUR SECONDARY LEAD SMELTER. DRUMS OF CLEAN UP DEBRIS AND PPE, AND A DRUM OF SPENT LIQUID WATER / ACID MIX ARE BEING TESTED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.   THE CAUSE OF THE FIRE WAS A SKID OF LARGE BATTERIES ARRANGED WITH THE TERMINAL POSTS TOWARD THE CENTER.  DIRECT CONTACT CAUSED A CLOSED CIRCUIT AND SHORTENED 2 BATTERIES FACING EACH OTHER. THE IGNITION WAS EXTREME ENOUGH TO MELT THE LEAD AND START THE CARDBOARD IN-BETWEEN THE LAYERS AND POSTS ON FIRE.
column169: TAILGATES WITH THE PRODUCTION PERSONNEL ON THE IMPORTANCE OF UTILIZING THE POST PROTECTORS AND PLACEMENT OF "HONEYCOMB" CARDBOARD BETWEEN TERMINALS WILL BE REVIEWED. VISUAL AIDS WILL ALSO BE MADE TO SHOW HOW TO PROPERLY PALLETIZE THIS STYLE BATTERY.

column168: ON SEPTEMBER 24, 2018, AT APPROXIMATELY 2:50 PM, AN EAST PENN TRUCK DRIVER WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ON ROUTE 313 FROM FREDERALSBURG, MD TO SALISBURG, MD IN HIS BOX TRUCK. HE HAD STOPPED AT THE 4 WAY INTERSECTION OF ROUTE 313 AND ROUTE 392 AT THE 4 WAY BLINKING TRAFFIC LIGHT. HE PROCEEDED STRAIGHT THROUGH THE INTERSECTION HEADING SOUTH ON ROUTE 313. THE DRIVER GLANCED AT THE DRIVER'S SIDE MIRROR. WHEN HE LOOKED FORWARD HIS PASSENGER SIDE WHEELS WERE ALREADY ON THE NARROW SHOULDER. THE ROAD WAS WET, WITH TALL GRASS ON THE SIDE AND A STEEP EDGE AND A DITCH ALONG SIDE. THERE WAS NO WAY OF CORRECTING THE TRUCK BACK ONTO THE ROAD. THE TRUCK WAS LEANING TOWARD THE PASSENGER SIDE AND CONTINUED STRAIGHT AHEAD AT WHICH POINT A UTILITY POLE LOCATED 10-12 FEET BACK FROM THE ROAD DESTROYED THE BOX OF THE TRUCK AS IT PASSED BY. ALL OF THE FREIGHT EMPTIED OUT OF THE TRUCK INTO THE DITCH AND CORN FIELD.   THE MARYLAND STATE POLICE ARRIVED AT THE SCENE. THE DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL FOR CHECK UP. THE LOCAL FIRE COMPANY WAS DISPATCHED AND SHORTLY ARRIVED AT THE SCENE TO CONTAIN THE INCIDENT. A HAZ MAT TEAM WAS ALSO DISPATCHED DUE IT BEING A LOAD OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL-LEAD ACID BATTERIES. THE GROUND AREA AND DITCH WERE BOTH DAMMED UP WITH PADS AND SOCKS AND ACID ABSORBENT WAS PUT DOWN. THE PH WAS MONITORED IN THE AREA AND WAS TESTED TO MAKE SURE IT WAS NEUTRAL. THE BATTERIES WERE PICKED UP AND PUT INTO TOTES TO CONTAIN ANY LEAKAGE. THE LOOSE SOIL WAS CLEANED UP AND LOADED INTO A ROLL OFF ALONG WITH THE ROOF OF THE TRUCK THAT WAS BADLY DAMAGED AND DAMAGED PALLETS AND BOXES. THE PH WAS CHECKED AGAIN BEFORE PICKING UP THE PADS AND SOCKS AND PUT INTO DISPOSAL BAGS ALONG WITH THE SPLASH SUITES THAT WERE ALSO PUT INTO THE ROLL OFF. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WASHED OFF THE ROAD AND THE GROUND AREA WAS FLUSHED. NO DIESEL WAS SPILLED. THE DIESEL THAT WAS LEFT INT HE TRUCK WAS PUMPED OUT AND COLLECTED TO HELP STABILIZE THE TRUCK TO AID IN PULLING IT OUT OF THE DITCH AND UP-RIGHTING IT. THE ENTIRE AREA WAS FILLED, LEVELED, RE-SEEDED AND CURLEX WAS PUT DOWN FOR STABILIZATION. THE POWER COMPANY CAME LATER TO INSPECT THE POLE. ALL WAS CLEARED BY 12:00 AM SEPTEMBER 25.  THE ROLL OFF IS BEING STORED AT AAA RECOVERY & SITE RESTORATION, LLC UNTIL IT IS FILLED. IT WILL THEN GO TO A LOCAL REGULAR LANDFILL IN DORCHESTER, MD FOR DISPOSAL. THE COLLECTED DIESEL FUEL IS ALSO BEING KEPT ONSITE AT AAA RECOVERY WHERE THEY ARE PERMITTED TO RE-USE IT IN THEIR OFF ROAD EQUIPMENT. A DRUM OF DEF WAS ALSO PUMPED OUT OF THE TRUCK. THIS IS ALSO BEING HELD AT AAA RECOVERY FOR DETERMINATION BY THE STATE REGARDING THE DISPOSAL/RECOVERY OR RECYCLING OF THE DEF. THE TOTES OF BATTERIES WERE INDIVIDUALLY BAGGED AND PUT ONTO PALLETS TO BE PICKED UP BY EAST PENN MANUFACTURING CO., TO BE DISPOSED OF AT OUR SECONDARY LEAD SMELTER.
column169: THE ACCIDENT WILL BE REVIEWED BY THE COMPANY'S ACCIDENT REVIEW COMMITTEE. OF THE DRIVER IS FOUND CHARGEABLE (DRIVE COULD HAVE PREVENTED), THE DRIVER WILL RECEIVE A DRIVER CODE OF CONDUCT VIOLATION. THIS WILL ALSO BE USED AS A TRAINING REASON ON DISTRACTED DRIVING.

column168: While unloading a shipment, the material noticed an unidentified red liquid had leaked from the bottom of the top box on the pallet onto the boxes below. The material immediately set the leaking container back into its original position and notified management of the release. The internal Blood Borne Pathogen protocol was put into effect and the entire pallet was placed into a safe area and cordoned off while waiting for the internal response team to arrive. Upon arrival, the response team assessed the situation, donned appropriate PPE and proceeded to over pack 4 boxes which had outside contamination into 85-gallon steel drums. The 4 over packs and all related clean up debris was shipped to its original destination without further incident.
column169: Discussions were held with the generators delivering medical waste to this facility stressing container closure and medical waste packaging guidelines. A tracking procedure will be put in place to track all medical waste boxed to be able to ascertain the actual generator in the chance of a future incident.

column168: At approximately 2:00pm on Thursday 4/5/18 approximately 10-15 gallons of Sodium Hydroxide 50% was spilled onto the ground.           Tank Farm EE’s were transferring Sodium Hydroxide 50% from railcar to storage tank when the hose became disconnected from the stationary transfer line and Sodium Hydroxide 50% residue proceeded to spray from the disconnected hose. Upon further investigation, it was found that when the railcar blew empty the surge of air pressure from the railcar caused the hose to become uncoupled from the cam lock connection. It was also found that a secondary securement device was not in place.           No product was allowed offsite or in any water drains. The spill was neutralized, cleaned up, and disposed of using proper PPE. No injuries or damage to report.
column169: Ensure employees are utilizing the second securement device on all fittings.    Retrain all Tank Farm Employees on the importance of using the Velcro straps that are available to secure the ears on all fittings.

column168: OUR DRIVER DELIVERED A LOAD OF INVIGORATE TO KINDER MORGAN IN INDIANAPOLIS, INDIANA. AS HE WAS PUMPING OFF A SMALL DRIP DEVELOPED OUT OF THE END OF HIS HOSE WHICH WAS CONTAINED IN A BUCKET. THE DRIVER THEN BROKE DOWN HIS HOSE TO SEE WHY IT WAS LEAKING. AS HE DRAINED THE HOSE INTO THE BUCKET IT OVER FLOWED AND CAUSED APPROXIMATELY 1-2 GALLONS OF PRODUCT TO SPILL ONTO THE GROUND. THE DRIVER MISCALCULATED HOW MUCH PRODUCT WAS IN THE HOSE AND CAUSED A SPILL. THE INITIAL PROBLEM OF THE LEAKING HOSE END WAS THE RESULT OF A COMPROMISED GASKET WHICH THE DRIVER CHANGED OUT. THE DRIVER CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL WITH ABSORBENT PADS. THIS WAS CONSIDERED A MINOR INCIDENT, AS THERE WEREN’T ANY INJURIES OR EXPOSURES.
column169: WHEN THE DRIVER RETURNED TO THE TERMINAL HE WAS SENT FOR A DRUG TEST WHICH HE PASSED. ADDITIONALLY, WE REVIEWED THE INCIDENT WITH THE DRIVER AND HAVE CONCLUDED THAT THE SPILL OCCURRED BECAUSE OF DRIVER ERROR. THE DRIVER FAILED TO PROPERLY INSPECT HIS HOSE/HOSE GASKET PRIOR TO USING HIS HOSE AND HE ALSO MISCALCULATED HOW MUCH PRODUCT WAS IN HIS HOSE WHEN HE WENT TO DRAIN IT. WE HAVE RE-TRAINED THE DRIVER ON THE PROPER WAY TO INSPECT AND DRAIN HIS HOSES. THE INCIDENT WILL BE DOCUMENTED IN HIS FILE AND GO ON HIS PERMANENT RECORD. LANGER TRANSPORT WILL DISCUSS THIS INCIDENT AT OUR NEXT DRIVERS MEETING IN AN EFFORT TO RAISE THE AWARENESS OF ALL THE DRIVERS IN THE FLEET.

column168: WAS TOLD THERE WAS A LEAKER. BEFORE I HEADED TO GET IT I WENT DOWN TO THE DMP AREA TO GET MY DECISION TREE. THE SUPERVISOR TOLD ME IT WAS NOT A REGULAR LEAKER AND THAT IT HAD A CORROSIVE HAZMAT STICKER ON THE SIDE. SO I PROCEEDED TO THE LEAKER, IN FULL REQUIRED PPE (SILVER LINER, GLOVES, APRON, BOOTS AND GOGGLES. GOT TO THE TRUCK THE UNLOADER WAS OUT ALREADY. I WENT IN AND ABOUT 10-15 BOXES INSIDE THE TRUCK WERE LEAKED ON. I HAD THE TRUCK MOVED TO ANOTHER BAY SO I COULD GET THE PACKAGES THAT GOT LEAKED ON. WENT TO THE BAY WHERE IT WAS MOVED, PUT THE PACKAGES ON A CART AND DROVE IT TO THE DMP AREA. I REBOXED ALL THE CONTAMINATED ONES AND SENT THEM OUT BECAUSE THEY WERE LIVE. NEXT I PROCEEDED TO THE MAIN LEAKER. SINCE IT WAS OVER 3 GALLONS I LEFT IT IN THE CONTAINER AND PUT CLAY-BASED AND SODIUM BICARBONATE ALONG WITH THE CONTAMINATED BOXES INSIDE A DMP GREEN BAG AND SENT IT TO THE B BUILDING.

column168: On 04/11/2018, at 2020 hours, a Federal Railroad Hazardous Materials Inspector in the CSXT Brooklyn Junction Yard discovered UTLX71690, a residue tank car of Sodium Hydroxide Solution, leaking from the vapor line valve. The car was isolated and the National Response Center, West Virginia Public Utilities Commission, and shipper were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report # 2018-0411-00304). Specialized Professional Services, Inc., a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the vapor line valve partially open and the secondary closure plug less than tool tight. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Mr. Tom Moppold, Sr. of Global Chemical Resources. Contractor personnel secured the valve and secondary closure. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required.  Cause Code: 134 NARRI: 90

column168: At 0430 hrs. while the Wheeling and Lake Erie Brewster Yard Car Inspector was inspecting the inbound train on an adjacent track, he was able to hear tank car CBTX 785903 hissing from the top of the car.  He called the Brewster Yardmaster to report the leak.  I, John Vergis Environmental Officer for the WLE, was then called by the WLE Chief Dispatcher to come out and look at the car.  When I arrived, I was able to hear vapor being released from the top of the car.  I removed seal number 36456 from the protective housing lid and then found that the vapor valve was leaking through the valve plug.  I tried to tighten the valve handle and when I did, the leak stopped.  I then tightened the loose valve plug.  I checked the liquid valves to see if the plugs were tight and they were not.  I tightened them.  I then installed seal number 971781 back on the protective housing and then released the car for service.  Also, on the car waybill and long train list, there was no proper basic description for the car.    NARRI:  5(4+5)X2=47                        Cause Code:379
column169: Better car securement procedures need followed.

column168: On 04/20/2018 at 1338 hours, personnel in the CSXT Demmler Yard discovered PPRX 55049, a loaded tank car of Isopentane, leaking from the protective housing. The car was isolated and the National Response Center, Pennsylvania DEP, and Phillips 66 were notified. (CHEMTREC Report # 2018-0420-00159). Joseph L. Taylor, a CSXT hazardous materials manager, was dispatched to the scene and found 2 of 4 liquid line to fittings plate flange securement bolts less than tool tight, resulting in a release. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Mr. Jeff Angle of Phillips 66. The securement bolts were properly secured and the release terminated. The tank car will required qualification by bubble leak test before it can be released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.  Cause Code: 284 NARRI:100
column169: Recommend an audit of the qualification process / shop to last qualify tank car. Leak point occurred below the operating valve.

While the driver was in the cab watching the pressure of air bags build up on the tanker which would tell him the tanker was full, the spill  occurred releasing approximately 75g of contaminated water onto the ground.  Sorbent material was immediately dispersed by the driver to contain the spill.  Clean Harbors F/S conducted remediation of the spilled area and removed the contaminated soil.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Deterioration or Aging; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: GATX 75432 had an odor coming from it in the Roseville Yard.  A vapor release was coming from the  PRD valve. This was confirmed with a bubble leak test. Both O-Rings were in worn condition and to small, replacing  them stopped the vapor release from the PRD. Then a vapor release was found at the vapor valve plug  threads. The valve was in the closed position and the plug was tool tight. The plugs threads were worn  and unable to create a proper seal. The plug was replaced which stopped the vapor release, the vapor  valve is defective. A vapor release was also found at the vapor valve flange, between the flange and  pressure plate. The flange bolts (all 4) were tool tight but not torqued correctly. The bolts were  tightened and the vapor release was stopped.

column168: Near the end of a delivery, Univar's driver noticed a drip coming from the underside of the trailer.  The trailer was already depressurizing as the delivery was almost complete.  Driver estimates no more than 5 gallons lost into the contained delivery area.  Driver assisted customer in clean up.  Our trailer was washed off and cleaned out at customer's site.  Upon inspection, it was discovered that the trailer has a crack in the bottom of barrel and is out of service until inspection and repairs can be made.  A chip in the inner liner was identified below the fill port and is the suspected cause of the leak.  Costs listed in question 32 are estimates.  As of submission of this report, the tanker trailer is waiting on approval to send to an approved repair facility in the southeastern USA for further investigation.  The listed carrier damage is the estimate to send the trailer to the repair facility for investigation.  Costs for repairs / replacement is not known at this time.

column168: Upon arrival at a delivery location, our driver noticed that two containers inside the trailer were leaking. After inspection by the driver, two containers were identified as damaged and leaking. Further investigation revealed that the dunnage placed to protect the freight was insufficient and resulted in the damage to the containers. The containers were immediately turned on their side to prevent further release. Absorbent material and the damaged containers were placed into an overpack for later disposal. Due to the hazard of material, the package specifications were unable to be obtained.
column169: If more sufficient blocking and bracing procedures were put in place, this incident may not have occurred. This incident along with other similar incidents will be used as a training tool during safety meetings in order to display the importance of using proper blocking and bracing techniques.
